You know, if you were
a Victorian scientist,

00:50:34.160 --> 00:50:37.410
and you go back, and you look at
the periodic table of elements,

00:50:37.410 --> 00:50:41.330
then it's true that there's
patterns in there that

00:50:41.330 --> 00:50:45.270
give a hint of the structure
that lies underneath.

00:50:45.270 --> 00:50:48.551
Those numbers that
repeat themselves.

00:50:48.551 --> 00:50:51.050
Where if you're very smart, you
might start to realise that,

00:50:51.050 --> 00:50:54.860
yes, there is something deeper
than just these elements.

00:50:54.860 --> 00:50:58.220
So our hope as theorists
is to look at this equation

00:50:58.220 --> 00:51:00.680
and see if maybe we
can just find patterns

00:51:00.680 --> 00:51:03.920
in this equation that suggest
there might be something

00:51:03.920 --> 00:51:06.760
deeper that lies underneath.

00:51:06.760 --> 00:51:08.150
And they're there.

00:51:08.150 --> 00:51:09.930
So let me give you an example.

00:51:09.930 --> 00:51:13.250
This is the equation
that describes the force

00:51:13.250 --> 00:51:16.340
of electricity and magnetism.

00:51:16.340 --> 00:51:19.250
And it's almost the same
as the equations which

00:51:19.250 --> 00:51:21.620
describe the forces
for the strong force

00:51:21.620 --> 00:51:24.030
and the weak nuclear force.

00:51:24.030 --> 00:51:24.530
You can see.

00:51:24.530 --> 00:51:26.902
I've just changed letters.

00:51:26.902 --> 00:51:28.610
It's a little more
complicated than that,

00:51:28.610 --> 00:51:30.710
but it's not much more
complicated than that.

00:51:30.710 --> 00:51:33.110
The three forces
really look similar.

00:51:33.110 --> 00:51:36.170
So you might wonder,
well, maybe there's not

00:51:36.170 --> 00:51:37.490
three forces in the universe.

00:51:37.490 --> 00:51:40.850
Maybe those three forces
are actually just one force.

00:51:40.850 --> 00:51:42.527
And when we think
there's three forces,

00:51:42.527 --> 00:51:44.360
it's because we're
looking at that one force

00:51:44.360 --> 00:51:47.510
just from slightly
different perspectives.

00:51:47.510 --> 00:51:49.084
Maybe.

00:51:49.084 --> 00:51:50.750
Here's something else,
which is amazing.

00:51:50.750 --> 00:51:54.320
These are the equations
for the 12 matter

00:51:54.320 --> 00:51:57.290
fields in the universe-- the
neutrinos, the electrons,

00:51:57.290 --> 00:51:58.850
and the quarks.

00:51:58.850 --> 00:52:02.180
Each of them obeys
exactly the same equation.

00:52:02.180 --> 00:52:04.890
Each of them obeys
the Dirac equation.

00:52:04.890 --> 00:52:06.360
So again, you
might wonder, well,

00:52:06.360 --> 00:52:07.985
maybe there aren't
12 different fields.

00:52:07.985 --> 00:52:11.540
Maybe they're all the same
field and the same particle,

00:52:11.540 --> 00:52:13.370
and the fact they look
different is, again,

00:52:13.370 --> 00:52:16.120
maybe just because
at them from slightly

00:52:16.120 --> 00:52:17.920
different perspectives.

00:52:17.920 --> 00:52:19.600
Maybe.

00:52:19.600 --> 00:52:22.960
So these ideas that
I've been suggesting

00:52:22.960 --> 00:52:25.090
go by the name of unification.

00:52:25.090 --> 00:52:28.240
The idea that the three forces
are actually combined into one

00:52:28.240 --> 00:52:30.790
is what's called
grand unification.

00:52:30.790 --> 00:52:31.660
And it's very easy.

00:52:31.660 --> 00:52:34.118
It's very easy to write down
a mathematical theory in which

00:52:34.118 --> 00:52:39.940
all of these are just one
force, which appears to be

00:52:39.940 --> 00:52:43.690
three from our perspective.

00:52:43.690 --> 00:52:45.200
There are other
possibilities here.

00:52:45.200 --> 00:52:47.710
You might say, well
this is the matter,

00:52:47.710 --> 00:52:49.570
and these are the forces.

00:52:49.570 --> 00:52:52.810
And the equations are different,
but they're not that different.

00:52:52.810 --> 00:52:55.480
Because ultimately,
they're both just fields.

00:52:55.480 --> 00:52:57.640
So you might wonder
if maybe there's

00:52:57.640 --> 00:52:59.860
some way in which the
matter and the forces

00:52:59.860 --> 00:53:02.500
are related to each other.

00:53:02.500 --> 00:53:04.560
Well, we have a theory
for that as well.

00:53:04.560 --> 00:53:06.670
It's a theory that's
called supersymmetry.

00:53:06.670 --> 00:53:08.050
And it's a beautiful theory.

00:53:08.050 --> 00:53:10.390
It's very deep conceptually.

00:53:10.390 --> 00:53:13.450
And it sort of, you know,
smells like it might be right.

00:53:13.450 --> 00:53:15.670
Finally, you might be
really, really bold.

00:53:15.670 --> 00:53:18.264
You might say, well, can
I just combine the lot?

00:53:18.264 --> 00:53:19.930
Can I just get rid
of all of these terms

00:53:19.930 --> 00:53:21.610
and just write down
one single term

00:53:21.610 --> 00:53:23.110
from which everything
else emerges?

00:53:23.110 --> 00:53:25.540
Gravity, the forces, the
particles, the Higgs,

00:53:25.540 --> 00:53:26.830
everything.

00:53:26.830 --> 00:53:29.170
I've got something for you
if you want that as well.

00:53:29.170 --> 00:53:30.760
It's called string theory.

00:53:30.760 --> 00:53:35.110
So we have a possibility for
a theory which contains all

00:53:35.110 --> 00:53:38.560
of this in one simple concept.

00:53:38.560 --> 00:53:42.020
And the question going forward,
of course, is are these right?

00:53:42.020 --> 00:53:45.546
You know, it's very easy for us
theorists to have these ideas.

00:53:45.546 --> 00:53:47.170
And I should say
these ideas are what's

00:53:47.170 --> 00:53:50.330
driven theoretical physics for
30 years, but we want to know,

00:53:50.330 --> 00:53:51.640
are they right?

00:53:51.640 --> 00:53:53.620
And we've got a way of
telling they're right.

00:53:53.620 --> 00:53:55.520
We do experiments.

00:53:55.520 --> 00:53:58.240
So I should say, if you want to
know if string theory's right,

00:53:58.240 --> 00:54:01.436
we don't have any way to
test it at the moment.

00:54:01.436 --> 00:54:04.060
But if you want to know if some
of these other ideas are right,

00:54:04.060 --> 00:54:06.520
then that's what the
LHC should be doing.

00:54:06.520 --> 00:54:09.420
The reason that we built the LHC
was firstly to find the Higgs.

00:54:09.420 --> 00:54:12.700
OK, it worked, and secondly,
to test these kind of ideas

00:54:12.700 --> 00:54:16.334
that we've been having
to see what lies beyond.

00:54:16.334 --> 00:54:17.500
So the LHC has been running.

00:54:17.500 --> 00:54:18.910
It's been running for two years.

00:54:18.910 --> 00:54:21.190
It's been running like
an absolute dream.

00:54:21.190 --> 00:54:22.960
It's a perfect machine.

00:54:22.960 --> 00:54:24.340
Two years.

00:54:24.340 --> 00:54:26.410
This is what it's seen.

00:54:26.410 --> 00:54:29.890
Absolutely nothing.

00:54:29.890 --> 00:54:33.070
All of these fantastic
beautiful ideas that we've had,

00:54:33.070 --> 00:54:37.090
none of them are
showing up at all.

00:54:37.090 --> 00:54:39.940
And the question going
forward is, what are we

00:54:39.940 --> 00:54:41.710
going to do about it?

00:54:41.710 --> 00:54:43.180
How are we going
to make progress

00:54:43.180 --> 00:54:45.620
in understanding the
next layer of physics

00:54:45.620 --> 00:54:47.290
when the LHC isn't
seeing anything,

00:54:47.290 --> 00:54:51.550
and our ideas just don't appear
to be the way that nature

00:54:51.550 --> 00:54:53.140
works?

00:54:53.140 --> 00:54:58.090
I should tell you, often I don't
have a good answer to this.

00:54:58.090 --> 00:54:59.860
My impression is that
most of my community

00:54:59.860 --> 00:55:03.272
is a little bit shell-shocked
by what happened.

00:55:03.272 --> 00:55:05.230
There's certainly no
consensus in the community

00:55:05.230 --> 00:55:06.890
to move forward.

00:55:06.890 --> 00:55:09.070
But I think there's
three responses

00:55:09.070 --> 00:55:11.290
that sort of various
people have had that I'd

00:55:11.290 --> 00:55:12.520
like to share with you.

00:55:12.520 --> 00:55:14.186
And I think all three
of these responses

00:55:14.186 --> 00:55:17.500
are reasonable up to a point.

00:55:17.500 --> 00:55:20.290
The first response to the
LHC not seeing anything

00:55:20.290 --> 00:55:23.410
is the following.

00:55:23.410 --> 00:55:26.240
You young kids,
you're so pessimistic.

00:55:26.240 --> 00:55:27.660
It's all doom and
gloom with you.

00:55:27.660 --> 00:55:29.380
You need a little
bit more patience.

00:55:29.380 --> 00:55:30.400
You know, I didn't see
anything last year,

00:55:30.400 --> 00:55:31.630
and I didn't see
anything this year.

00:55:31.630 --> 00:55:33.610
But next year, it's
going to see something.

00:55:33.610 --> 00:55:35.610
And if not next year,
it's the year after that

00:55:35.610 --> 00:55:36.985
that it's going
to see something.

00:55:36.985 --> 00:55:40.390
It's usually my very
illustrious senior colleagues

00:55:40.390 --> 00:55:41.770
that have this--

00:55:41.770 --> 00:55:42.520
and you know what?

00:55:42.520 --> 00:55:44.140
They could easily be right.

00:55:44.140 --> 00:55:46.640
It could easily be that
next year, the LHC discovers

00:55:46.640 --> 00:55:48.190
something astonishing,
and it sets us

00:55:48.190 --> 00:55:53.200
on the path to understanding
the next layer of reality.

00:55:53.200 --> 00:55:55.420
But it's also true
that these same people

00:55:55.420 --> 00:55:58.310
were predicting that it would
have seen something by now.

00:55:58.310 --> 00:56:00.940
And it's also true
that this can't

00:56:00.940 --> 00:56:02.980
keep going for much longer.

00:56:02.980 --> 00:56:05.800
If the LHC doesn't see something
within, say, a two-year time

00:56:05.800 --> 00:56:08.710
scale, it seems
very, very unlikely

00:56:08.710 --> 00:56:11.590
that it's going to see
something moving forward.

00:56:11.590 --> 00:56:12.910
It's possible.

00:56:12.910 --> 00:56:14.780
It just seems unlikely.

00:56:14.780 --> 00:56:18.820
So I hope with all my heart
that the LHC discover something

00:56:18.820 --> 00:56:21.110
next year or the year after.

00:56:21.110 --> 00:56:23.120
But I think we have to
prepare for the worst,

00:56:23.120 --> 00:56:24.740
that maybe it won't.

00:56:24.740 --> 00:56:25.240
OK.

00:56:25.240 --> 00:56:26.640
Response number two.

00:56:26.640 --> 00:56:31.300
Response number two, which is
sort of also by similar people,

00:56:31.300 --> 00:56:33.040
well, all our theories
are so beautiful.

00:56:33.040 --> 00:56:34.498
They absolutely
have to be correct,

00:56:34.498 --> 00:56:37.480
and what we really need
is a bigger machine.

00:56:37.480 --> 00:56:40.810
10 times bigger will do it.

00:56:40.810 --> 00:56:43.090
Again, they might be right.

00:56:43.090 --> 00:56:45.190
I don't have a good
argument against it.

00:56:45.190 --> 00:56:47.500
The obvious rebuttal,
however, is that a new machine

00:56:47.500 --> 00:56:48.670
cost $10 billion.

00:56:48.670 --> 00:56:52.180
There's not too many
governments in the world

00:56:52.180 --> 00:56:57.350
that have $10 billion to spare
for us to explore these ideas.

00:56:57.350 --> 00:56:58.230
There's one.

00:56:58.230 --> 00:56:59.326
The one is China.

00:56:59.326 --> 00:57:01.450
And so if this machine is
going to be built at all,

00:57:01.450 --> 00:57:03.491
it's going to be built by
the Chinese government.

00:57:03.491 --> 00:57:06.130
I think the Chinese government
would see it as extremely

00:57:06.130 --> 00:57:08.689
attractive if the whole
community of particle

00:57:08.689 --> 00:57:10.480
physicists and engineers
that are currently

00:57:10.480 --> 00:57:13.290
based in CERN and Geneva
move to a town that's

00:57:13.290 --> 00:57:14.890
slightly north of Beijing.

00:57:14.890 --> 00:57:18.160
I think they'd view that as
political and economic gain,

00:57:18.160 --> 00:57:19.990
and there's a real
chance they may

00:57:19.990 --> 00:57:21.550
decide to build this machine.

00:57:21.550 --> 00:57:25.160
If they do, it's about 20
years for it to be built.

00:57:25.160 --> 00:57:29.210
So we're waiting
slightly longer.

00:57:29.210 --> 00:57:32.260
There's a third response.

00:57:32.260 --> 00:57:34.080
And I should say
the third response

00:57:34.080 --> 00:57:36.370
is kind of the camp I'm in.

00:57:36.370 --> 00:57:38.650
I should mention upfront,
it's speculative ,

00:57:38.650 --> 00:57:42.220
and it's probably not
endorsed by most of my peers.

00:57:42.220 --> 00:57:46.630
So this is really just my
personal opinion at this point.

00:57:46.630 --> 00:57:48.893
This is my take on this.

00:57:53.530 --> 00:57:58.030
This is the equation
that we know is right.

00:57:58.030 --> 00:58:00.580
This is sort of the bedrock
of our understanding.

00:58:00.580 --> 00:58:02.560
But although we know
it's right, there's

00:58:02.560 --> 00:58:06.850
an awful lot in this equation
that we haven't understood.

00:58:06.850 --> 00:58:09.040
There's an awful lot
to me that's still

00:58:09.040 --> 00:58:11.689
mysterious in this equation.

00:58:11.689 --> 00:58:13.480
So although this equation
looked like there

00:58:13.480 --> 00:58:16.330
were suggestions of
unification, maybe they're

00:58:16.330 --> 00:58:17.950
just red herrings.

00:58:17.950 --> 00:58:20.380
And maybe if we just
work harder in trying

00:58:20.380 --> 00:58:22.990
to understand this
equation more,

00:58:22.990 --> 00:58:27.890
we'll find that there are
other patterns that emerge.

00:58:27.890 --> 00:58:30.460
So my response is, I think
that maybe we should just

00:58:30.460 --> 00:58:34.360
go back to the drawing
board and start

00:58:34.360 --> 00:58:37.300
to challenge some of the
assumptions and paradigms

00:58:37.300 --> 00:58:40.490
that we've been holding
for the past 30 years.

00:58:40.490 --> 00:58:43.240
So I feel quite
energised, actually,

00:58:43.240 --> 00:58:44.830
by the lack of
results for the LHC.

00:58:44.830 --> 00:58:45.610
You know?

00:58:45.610 --> 00:58:48.130
Sort of it feels good to
me that everyone was wrong.

00:58:48.130 --> 00:58:52.040
You know, it's when we're wrong
that we start to make progress.

00:58:52.040 --> 00:58:55.600
So I sort of feel
quite happy about this,

00:58:55.600 --> 00:58:59.600
and think that there's a very
real chance that we could just

00:58:59.600 --> 00:59:01.660
start thinking about
different ideas.

00:59:01.660 --> 00:59:04.240
I should say that there
are hints in here.

00:59:04.240 --> 00:59:06.670
There are hints to me
about mathematical patterns

00:59:06.670 --> 00:59:08.130
that we haven't explored.

00:59:08.130 --> 00:59:09.940
There's hints in this
about connections

00:59:09.940 --> 00:59:11.170
to other areas of science.

00:59:11.170 --> 00:59:12.711
Things like condensed
matter physics,

00:59:12.711 --> 00:59:14.620
which is the science
of how materials work,

00:59:14.620 --> 00:59:17.950
or quantum information
science, which is the attempt

00:59:17.950 --> 00:59:19.450
to build a quantum computer.

00:59:19.450 --> 00:59:22.720
All these fantastic
subjects have new ideas,

00:59:22.720 --> 00:59:25.960
which sort of feed in
to the kind of questions

00:59:25.960 --> 00:59:27.400
that we're asking here.

00:59:27.400 --> 00:59:30.940
So I'm quite optimistic
that moving forward,

00:59:30.940 --> 00:59:33.310
we can make progress,
maybe not the progress

00:59:33.310 --> 00:59:36.610
that we thought we'd make a few
years ago, but just something

00:59:36.610 --> 00:59:38.780
new.

00:59:38.780 --> 00:59:40.330
So that's the
punchline of my talk.

00:59:40.330 --> 00:59:45.570
The punchline is that this is
the single greatest equation

00:59:45.570 --> 00:59:47.740
that we've ever written down.

00:59:47.740 --> 00:59:52.680
But I hope that someday, we
can give you something better.

00:59:52.680 --> 00:59:54.460
Thank you for your attention.

00:59:54.460 --> 00:59:58.187
[APPLAUSE]

00:59:58.187 --> 01:00:00.520
There's nothing discrete about
the Schrodinger equation.

01:00:00.520 --> 01:00:03.500
The Schrodinger
equation is something

01:00:03.500 --> 01:00:07.502
to do with a smooth
field-like wave function.

01:00:07.502 --> 01:00:08.960
The discreteness
is something which

01:00:08.960 --> 01:00:11.070
emerges when you solve
the Schrodinger equation.

01:00:11.070 --> 01:00:13.900
So it's not built into
the heart of nature.

